Location.Notes: On the shore of a small creek (average width under 15-20 feet, average depth would be a foot or so). A few hundred yards from Edsall Road in Alexandria, VA.
Observation.Notes: Very interesting behavior. It landed on top of my sister's soaking wet sandals and preceded the drink the water out of the sandal material. It stayed there for at least 3 minutes and was very unafraid. It even climbed on her finger briefly before flying off.

Observation.Notes: It had been seen daily for a few weeks, feeding off of the neighbor's bushes and resting in my walnut trees.

I moved him to a nearby fern to get him off the driveway.  There is a magnolia tree that overhangs the driveway and lilacs (not in bloom) also nearby.

Observation.Notes: It was a clear, hot and humid night. I spotted it on my screen door at ~midnight, and it remained there (despite gently opening and closing the door several times to go outside) all night. I got it to spread it's wings for a photo by very gently blowing on it. Finally disappeared once the sun rose, last sighting around 7 am. I did not have my porch light on when I first spotted it, so I'm not sure what attracted it to my door - it is normally an insect jamboree with the light on, but not off.

Location.Notes: In back yard garden at pentas. This was the 4th time this month I have seen Papilio glaucus (all were males) and the only photograph I could get. I saw them Jan. 14, 20, 25, and today, all in my garden at or near the pentas. This January has been the warmest since 1974 and no hard freeze has been experienced here this winter, hence pentas, salvia and spanish needle still in bloom. Also saw Papilio troilus (male) on Jan. 25 and several long-tailed skippers (no photos).

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Observation.Notes: The butterfly has the same flight pattern in the yard, coming from the West traveling East across the yard. It starts with the same flowers pictured, traveling to each one (there are at least 15-20), moves to the Marigolds briefly, then goes to a flowering bush on the East side of the yard and moves on. It will appear back on the West side of the yard and do this a few times before leaving for the day. It comes back every morning at the same time. When the birds are in the garden while it is, the butterfly darts into the air traveling quickly as if mimicking a bird, then back onto the flower tops. The butterfly has been here most of July and now into August. It is visible on days when it is sunny and warm out.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus

Observation.Notes: It was a sunny, calm morning with some clouds.  The tiger swallowtail was drinking nectar from the Mexican sunflowers, and it stayed a long time around 25 minutes.  During that time, there was a giant swallowtail, a type of sulphur, and a black swallowtail.  They took turns with the flowers.  At one point, the giant swallowtail swooped towards the tiger swallowtail and they twirled around each other for a second before going separate ways.  The black swallowtail and the sulphur didn't stick around for more than a minute.

Observation.Notes: I was in the garage, and randomly saw this butterfly struggling on the floor! went to pick it up, and it flew up to my shoulder and hung on until I got outside. It let me set it down on our blooming origami roses, looked away for a split second and it was gone! Like it disappeared in to thin air . every season my family and I grow a butterfly garden and help track monarchs as well as rear our own and release.. And I've never experienced anything like that! It was so strange! Mystical in a way.

Location.Notes: He was lying on the sidewalk, attempting to fly.
Observation.Notes: I found him on the sidewalk as I was going to class, there were some trees nearby but not many bushes or flowers. He was trying to fly but couldn't get off the ground. The bottom of his right wing was torn. I watched him for a while. He soon stopped trying to fly and rested for a long time then extended his proboscis, wrapped his legs around it, and vibrated for a while before dying. I brought him into my class which is where the picture is taken. As for weather conditions, it was about 84 degrees Fahrenheit outside, high in humidity, and looked like it was going to rain but did not.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Location.Notes: These butterflies were sighted over the creek that runs between my apartment complex and another one, across the creek.  The location was near the bend in the creek where there's heavy forest-remnant undergrowth.  There was a tall plant with ball-shaped flowers/fruit with spikes that was hanging over the creek from the other side.  The butterflies were flitting all over these flowers/fruit.
Observation.Notes: On a warm, June day around noon, I noticed a lot of activity over the creek where there was  heavy forest-remnant undergrowth.  There was a swarm of 6-8 large swallowtail butterflies flitting around some ball-shaped flowers/fruit that had spikes. These were growing on some tall woodland plant that was hanging over the creek near the bend. I saw this activity in June, 2010. Never before and never since.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Observation.Notes: Found this insect on the ground under a tree, unable to fly. It was desperately trying to fly, but couldn't lift off the ground at all. In fact, it seemed determined to remain on it's back. When I sat him up right, he just continued to flop around. It became lethargic, so I tried giving it some fruit. The next day, it released some red-brown watery stuff from it's bottom and then died a few hours later. After the insect died and I spread it, I noticed the top set of wings had to be forced out and before it's death, it didn't seem like it could spread them to fly, either.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Observation.Notes: Saw TWO Eastern Tiger Swallowtails, seemingly flying together, at the park flying around the butterfly garden beds which featured Butterfly Bushes, Zinnias, Black-eyed Susans, Portuluca, Blue Salvia, Pink Angelonia and Purple  Fountain Grass. They seemed to prefer the white Butterfly Bush best (as did many other flying insects). Enclosing photos of both here. One of them had their left hind wing and tail chewed/missing. When they got on a blossom to nectar they beat their wings furiously, finally stopping very briefly to nectar,  then would fly to the next spot, and again beat their wings furiously, then calm down, quickly nectar, sail to the next blossom, etc. Didn't mind me getting quite close  to photograph them. Weather: 95 degrees, 40-45% humidity, sunny. Approx. size: 4" wingspan

Observation.Notes: Hello Mike! Asclepias tuberosa is a reliable draw for some species. This raggedy Eastern Tiger Swallowtail couldn't get enough and totally ignored my picture taking. Didn't see her on any of their host plants and could not find any eggs. Shortly after this sighting we had a devastating hail storm which really hit insects and birds hard, with action just now picking up again. Have only seen one other "tiger" this year in early June on Canada Red Chokecherry, couldn't confirm species or sex, obviously no chance for picture either. Thanks, Char

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Observation.Notes: Dark morph female, SO HUGE, bigger than the Giant Swallowtail I saw the other day. Was flying in and through the butterfly flower bed at the county extension demonstration gardens, mostly feeding on the Joe-Pye Weed, flying through it and landing on different blossoms. Watched it for about 15 minutes doing this. At one point, it and the black swallowtail I also saw flew up in the sky together, and the black swallowtail was majorly dwarfed by the size of this butterfly. Best part was towards the end of my time watching it when it let me get the closest I've ever gotten to a large butterfly that's feeding before, with it being about 3" from my face, just watching it! Size: Approx. 6" wingspan, if not larger, biggest butterfly I've ever seen. Weather: 89 degrees, 56% humidity, sunny skies.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Location.Notes: Approximately 4 miles from Norfolk VA  mile post marker, near the Indian River.
Observation.Notes: The body is black without any white vertical or horizontal lines and very large - a little larger than the tiger Swallowtail.  The upper top side of the fore wing has a small white line on it.  In three of the pictures ( one butterfly) the line is fainter. It stays stationary on a flower for considerable time ( approx. 30 sec.) and is undisturbed by my taking close up pictures from various angles. The wingspan is possibly a little larger then the Tiger Swallowtail when I see them together. There are two distinct orange spots on the top of the hind wing - one at each end of the margin of the hind wing.  One of the enclosed pictures reflects them.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Location.Notes:
Nature Preserve called Wingate Prairie
Wingate Prairie is 39 acres of a very rare gravel hill prairie. The natural area is precious because only 59 acres of gravel hill prairie are known to exist in Illinois. In 1994, the Illinois Nature Preserve Commission designated the prairie as an Illinois Nature Preserve. Only sites with statewide ecological value are considered for this highest level of protection under Illinois law. This unique prairie land, with its rolling terrain, oak savanna and conifer groupings, is home to several rare and endangered plant and animal species including the Prairie Buttercup, Pinweed, Queen of the Prairie, Pale Vetchling, Purple Flowering Raspberry, Silvery Blue Butterfly, and the Franklin Ground Squirrel. During its active months from spring to fall, the prairie is in constant bloom. Nature lovers are welcomed by hiking trails that are moderate to very hilly that meander through the prairie. From hill to hollow, the type of native vegetation waiting to be discovered varies. A flat moraine at the northern end of the site is home to yet another variety of plants not requiring the well-drained soil of the hills or the damp hollow areas.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Location.Notes: This town main street is small, less than two blocks including town hall. This location is about 2 blocks from the Rock Island nature trail. General area is agricultural. The tea room across the street has a sizeable garden filled with roses, trumpet vine, lillies,  and many  others. My courtyard has sunflowers, snap dragons, cone flowers, salvia, geraniums and others.
Observation.Notes: Construction worker walked over and handed me what appeared to be an injured butterfly, perhaps because there are butterflies on my sign? It seemed dazed, possible with an injured leg, Friend and I put it in my flower bed, broke off a cone type flower and drenched it in water then placed it next to the butterfly. We kept a close eye on it. It wasn't moving but after a while started moving it's wings slightly. About an hour later it had moved to feeding off the flower but didn't leave it. It opened and closed its wings.  I kept watching and a couple of hours later it was still there. The next morning it was gone. I looked everywhere. This afternoon a few days later I stopped by my shop. I was in the courtyard and what appeared to be the same or perhaps a similar butterfly swooped by and flew around in front of me and disappeared around the corner. I had not seen this type of butterfly previously. I have always liked butterflies but began seeing them more frequently when I was diagnosed with a brain tumor. I don't know why probably I started paying more attention to them. When I went on my first survivor walk (which I really didn't want to be at) a monarch flew into my group and began circling around next to me. I have a newfound appreciation for life and butterflies. I was very, very lucky to have a non-cancerous tumor and really no effects after 7 1/2 hours of brain surgery. I quit my corporate job, opened an art gallery and my logo has a butterfly as part of it. The courtyard of that gallery is where my friend (who designed my logo) and I were when presented with the injured, or maybe just dazed butterfly.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Observation.Notes: Found in a heavily shaded area very low to the ground. Closer observation revealed that this butterfly was laying eggs on the low lying plant. Even when I got right up to it, she would never fly more than a couple of leaves away from me on the same plant. Only spotted two eggs, but considering she was already flying around the plant when I found her, I suspect that there are more. Eggs were visibly laid on the top of the plant leaves singly, before she would move on to another leaf. Weather was partly cloudy with periodical gaps of clear blue skies.

Scientific.Name: Papilio glaucus
Location.Notes: The butterfly was feeding in a blooming tree/large bush (that looks like an Aesculus sp., perhaps A. parviflora) next to the Lakeview Nature Center at Lakeview Nature Area, a well-reestablished tallgrass prairie.  These are all one individual, but there were several of these feeding on the same tree.  I photographed this one individual over several minutes before moving on to something else at just a few feet away, and these are just a few of the total number taken.
